          <li>Helps manage side effects (e.g., switching from myrcene-heavy to pinene-forward profile).</li>
          <li>Enhances <strong>patient empowerment</strong> by enabling dialogue around terpenes in strain selection.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="wp-subsection-heading">9. Recent &amp; Emerging Research (2019&ndash;2024)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>2021 <em>Scientific Reports:</em> Terpenes (humulene, linalool, geraniol, &beta;-pinene) showed cannabimimetic effects in mice.</li>
          <li>NIH trial ongoing: Myrcene &amp; &beta;-Caryophyllene for pain (potential THC/opioid-sparing).</li>
          <li>Lavender (linalool) and lemon oil (limonene) RCTs for anxiety and mood now underway.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="wp-subsection-heading">10. Cautions in Translation</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Doses in animal studies often exceed realistic human exposures.</li>
          <li>Individual sensitivity varies widely &rarr; titrate slowly.</li>
          <li>Purity/source matters when isolating or compounding terpenes for inhalation/ingestion.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="wp-subsection-heading">11. Summary</h3>
        <p>
          Terpenes are potent therapeutic agents within cannabis, with specific receptor targets, kinetic profiles, and clinical actions. By understanding and applying terpene pharmacology, clinicians can deliver more <strong>personalised, effective, and synergistic care</strong>. As research evolves, terpenes are shifting from "aromatic extras" to <em>strategic therapeutic modulators</em> within modern cannabinoid medicine.
        </p>
