        <!-- ─────────────────── 6. α-HUMULENE ─────────────────── -->
        <h3 id="humulene" class="wp-subsection-heading">6. &alpha;-Humulene (&alpha;-Caryophyllene)</h3>

        <div class="wp-terpene-profile">
          <strong>Profile:</strong> Sesquiterpene (C<sub>15</sub>H<sub>24</sub>) isomeric with &beta;-caryophyllene. Humulene is found in hops (<em>Humulus lupulus</em>, hence the name), cannabis, sage, and ginseng. Aroma is woody, earthy with subtle spicy notes &mdash; it contributes to the &ldquo;hoppy&rdquo; beer smell. In cannabis, often present alongside BCP. Boiling point: ~166&ndash;169&thinsp;&deg;C at 1 atm. Colorless to pale yellow oil; insoluble in water, soluble in organics. Fairly stable if stored properly.
        </div>

        <p><strong>Receptor Targets:</strong> Humulene does not directly activate cannabinoid receptors like its isomer BCP, but it influences inflammatory pathways. It has been shown to inhibit <strong>NF-&kappa;B signalling</strong> by blocking I&kappa;B-&alpha; degradation in activated cells (thus preventing NF-&kappa;B translocation to the nucleus). It also inhibits <strong>TNF-&alpha; and IL-1&beta; release</strong> from immune cells. Humulene likely interacts with intracellular signalling rather than a single receptor &mdash; possibly affecting kinases like MAPK or enzymes like COX-2. Some studies suggest humulene might weakly activate <strong>PPAR&alpha;</strong>, a nuclear receptor that modulates inflammation and metabolism.</p>

        <p><strong>Mechanisms of Action:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Anti-inflammatory:</strong> Humulene&rsquo;s hallmark. It reduces production of key pro-inflammatory mediators: TNF-&alpha;, IL-1&beta;, IL-6, and nitric oxide in immune cells. It downregulates <strong>COX-2 and iNOS expression</strong> at the transcriptional level. One rodent study showed that oral humulene significantly reduced carrageenan-induced paw inflammation, with efficacy comparable to the steroid dexamethasone.</li>
          <li><strong>Analgesic:</strong> By reducing inflammation, it indirectly relieves pain behavior in some models even in the absence of overt inflammation, implying some central or peripheral nociceptor modulation.</li>
          <li><strong>Anti-allergic:</strong> Humulene exhibited anti-allergic properties in one study (inhibiting histamine release from mast cells).</li>
          <li><strong>Appetite-suppressant:</strong> Interestingly, humulene is reported to <strong>reduce appetite</strong> (contrasting most cannabis components). In some folk medicine, hops (with humulene) were noted to decrease hunger.</li>
          <li><strong>Antibacterial:</strong> Humulene has modest antibiotic activity against Staph aureus and certain Gram-positives, and anti-fungal effect on dermatophytes.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Therapeutic Effects:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Inflammatory pain conditions:</strong> Humulene could be particularly beneficial in arthritis, bursitis, or autoimmune inflammatory pain. A rat arthritis model found humulene significantly reduced joint swelling and pain-related behaviors. It also lowered systemic inflammation markers. Combined with &beta;-caryophyllene, humulene&rsquo;s effect is amplified.</li>
          <li><strong>Topical anti-inflammatory:</strong> Humulene is a skin penetrant and has been used topically in traditional medicine. It can reduce allergic contact dermatitis and edema in skin when applied, comparable to topical steroid in effect.</li>
          <li><strong>Asthma:</strong> By inhibiting inflammatory mediators, humulene might help allergic asthma &mdash; a study in guinea pigs found humulene reduced Ovalbumin-induced airway inflammation.</li>
          <li><strong>Cancer:</strong> Preliminary research indicates humulene can suppress cancer cell proliferation and induce apoptosis in some tumor cell lines. Far from clinical use but a note of interest.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Pharmacokinetics:</strong> Likely similar to &beta;-caryophyllene (since they are isomers). Humulene is absorbed orally but there&rsquo;s limited data. Given BCP&rsquo;s known kinetics (T<sub>max</sub> ~1h, distributed, not immediately metabolized), humulene may behave similarly. Humulene&rsquo;s boiling point is about 106&thinsp;&deg;C at 5 mmHg (~166&thinsp;&deg;C at 1 atm range), so in vaping some humulene will vaporize in the mid-high range. Metabolism possibly via CYP3A4 and epoxide hydrolases to humulene-1,2-epoxide and others. T<sub>&frac12;</sub> few hours (estimated). <strong>Topical:</strong> humulene can penetrate skin especially if formulated in a carrier oil.</p>

        <p><strong>Synergistic Pairings:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>With &beta;-Caryophyllene:</strong> This is a classic synergy. A study found &alpha;-humulene and trans-caryophyllene together &ldquo;were comparable to dexamethasone&rdquo; in an animal inflammation model. They likely cover slightly different inflammatory pathways, providing a broader suppression.</li>
          <li><strong>With THC/CBD:</strong> Adding humulene can directly suppress inflammatory mediator production, complementing cannabinoids. In chronic pain patients, a CBD:THC extract with humulene might better reduce joint swelling or inflammatory pain flares.</li>
          <li><strong>With &beta;-Pinene or other anti-inflammatories:</strong> There is synergy with other anti-inflammatory terpenes like pinene (they can target different pathways &mdash; pinene might block inflammatory prostaglandins, humulene TNF&alpha;; together stronger effect).</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Drug Interactions:</strong> In theory, humulene could add to the effect of NSAIDs or steroids (a positive interaction). There&rsquo;s no known negative interaction. If a patient is on immunosuppressive therapy, adding an anti-inflammatory terpene like humulene might further reduce immune activity &mdash; realistic terpene doses likely won&rsquo;t dangerously immunosuppress. Humulene is not sedative, and doesn&rsquo;t have a known direct psychoactive effect to interact with those drugs.</p>

        <p><strong>Toxicity &amp; Safety:</strong> <strong>Safe in moderate exposure.</strong> Humans have consumed humulene via hops in beer and herbal medicines for a long time. It&rsquo;s not known to be toxic. LD<sub>50</sub>: likely &gt;5g/kg (extrapolating from caryophyllene). Not classified as carcinogen. Humulene is less pungent than pinene and generally less irritating. Humulene&rsquo;s oxidation products could cause contact dermatitis, but no specific common allergy is noted in literature.</p>

        <div class="section-divider"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>

        <!-- ─────────────────── 7. NEROLIDOL ─────────────────── -->
        <h3 id="nerolidol" class="wp-subsection-heading">7. Nerolidol (Trans-Nerolidol)</h3>

        <div class="wp-terpene-profile">
          <strong>Profile:</strong> Sesquiterpene alcohol (C<sub>15</sub>H<sub>26</sub>O) with a delicate floral, citrus, and woody aroma. Found in jasmine, tea tree, lemongrass, and some cannabis (often as a minor terpene). Two isomers (trans and cis); trans-nerolidol is common. Nerolidol imparts a &ldquo;waxy, fresh bark&rdquo; scent. Boiling point: ~252&thinsp;&deg;C (quite high, reflecting its low volatility). Viscous liquid at room temp. Pleasant, floral-citrus with woody undertone. Practically insoluble in water, mixes with oils. Fairly stable due to being an alcohol.
        </div>

        <p><strong>Receptor Targets:</strong> As a sesquiterpene alcohol, nerolidol likely acts similarly to linalool in modulating GABA<sub>A</sub> receptors. It may also influence <strong>adenosine</strong> or <strong>opioid</strong> receptors indirectly (one study in mice indicated that a metabolite of nerolidol interacted with opioid receptors). <strong>TRP channels:</strong> Nerolidol has been reported to activate <strong>TRPV3</strong> (a warmth-sensitive channel in skin). <strong>P-glycoprotein (P-gp) inhibitor</strong> in cell assays &mdash; P-gp is an efflux pump; nerolidol inhibiting it means it can increase penetration of drugs into cells (that&rsquo;s why it&rsquo;s studied as a skin penetration enhancer and brain penetration enhancer).</p>

        <p><strong>Mechanisms of Action:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sedative/Hypnotic:</strong> Nerolidol produces sedation by <strong>enhancing GABAergic neurotransmission</strong>. In rodents, nerolidol decreased locomotion and increased sleep time.</li>
          <li><strong>Anxiolytic:</strong> With sedation comes anxiolysis &mdash; nerolidol has shown anti-anxiety effects in elevated maze tests, presumably because of general CNS depression.</li>
          <li><strong>Analgesic:</strong> Nerolidol has analgesic and anti-inflammatory effects: it reduced pain responses in inflammatory and neuropathic pain models. A study with neuropathic pain found nerolidol reduced pain behaviors by modulating spinal cord oxidative stress and inflammation markers.</li>
          <li><strong>Anti-parasitic:</strong> Nerolidol is notably effective against parasites &mdash; it can kill malaria parasites and leishmania in cell culture. It helps other drugs get into parasite cells by inhibiting P-gp.</li>
          <li><strong>Antimicrobial:</strong> Good against bacteria and fungi (like candida), as it disrupts cell membranes.</li>
          <li><strong>Skin penetration enhancement:</strong> Mechanistically, nerolidol intercalates into lipid membranes in the skin, increasing their fluidity and allowing other molecules to penetrate more readily. This makes nerolidol useful in topical drug formulations.</li>
          <li><strong>Antioxidant:</strong> Nerolidol scavenges free radicals and reduces lipid peroxidation in tissues under stress.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Therapeutic Effects:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sleep aid:</strong> Nerolidol appears to be a strong sedative. It&rsquo;s been less publicized than linalool or myrcene, but some cannabis analysis show high nerolidol in strains reputed to be very relaxing. Particularly useful in formulations for insomnia.</li>
          <li><strong>Topical pain/inflammation:</strong> Nerolidol&rsquo;s penetration enhancement plus analgesic/anti-inflammatory effect make it great for topicals. A CBD cream with nerolidol could deliver CBD deeper to tissues and also directly reduce local inflammation.</li>
          <li><strong>Neurodegenerative diseases:</strong> There is interest in nerolidol for neurodegeneration because it crosses the blood-brain barrier and has antioxidant and anti-inflammatory effects in the brain.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Pharmacokinetics:</strong> <strong>Oral:</strong> Nerolidol may be somewhat more water-soluble than hydrocarbon terpenes, but still largely lipophilic. It likely has decent oral absorption and distributed well. T<sub>&frac12;</sub> likely a few hours. It may undergo first-pass metabolism that reduces its bioavailability somewhat. <strong>Inhaled:</strong> Nerolidol&rsquo;s boiling point is high (~252&thinsp;&deg;C), so not all of it vaporizes during typical vaping; however, if present, some portion will volatilize. <strong>Topical:</strong> Nerolidol penetrates stratum corneum effectively &mdash; studies measuring skin content found high nerolidol levels after applying nerolidol-containing formulations. It can even reach systemic circulation from a transdermal application to some extent.</p>

        <p><strong>Synergistic Pairings:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>With other sedative terpenes (linalool, myrcene):</strong> The sedation could become very strong &mdash; perhaps too strong except for severe insomnia. But in a balanced formula, a bit of nerolidol can complement linalool.</li>
          <li><strong>With cannabinoids for sleep/pain:</strong> A THC or CBN-heavy preparation with nerolidol would likely be extremely soporific, useful for refractory insomnia. For pain, THC/CBD cover central and some peripheral pain; nerolidol adds anti-inflammatory and local analgesic benefit.</li>
          <li><strong>With other terpenes for skin applications:</strong> For topicals, adding nerolidol can enhance penetration of BCP or CBD through skin, boosting efficacy. Also, combining nerolidol with terpenes like eucalyptol or menthol might create both penetration and immediate cooling/warming sensation synergy.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Drug Interactions:</strong> <strong>CNS depressants:</strong> Additive sedation (as with all sedative terpenes). <strong>Drugs using P-gp efflux:</strong> Nerolidol&rsquo;s P-gp inhibition means it can increase bioavailability of certain drugs. For example, cancer drugs or HIV protease inhibitors that are P-gp substrates might have higher levels if nerolidol is chronically used. At the levels from normal cannabis use, it&rsquo;s probably negligible. <strong>CYP interactions:</strong> Some research suggests nerolidol inhibits CYP3A4 and induces phase II enzymes &mdash; at high-dose nerolidol (like a concentrated terpene supplement) regularly, it might slow metabolism of drugs like midazolam, cyclosporine, etc.</p>

        <p><strong>Toxicity &amp; Safety:</strong> <strong>Safe within typical use.</strong> Nerolidol is in foods (as flavor, in tea, etc.) and used in cosmetics. It&rsquo;s generally recognized as safe as a flavor agent. High doses in animals: a study giving rats 250 mg/kg nerolidol for 14 days saw no lethal effects, just slight enzyme changes. So relatively low toxicity. <strong>Sedation caution:</strong> Too much can cause stupor or loss of coordination. As an alcohol, nerolidol is less volatile, so it&rsquo;s not a big inhalation irritant. Not a common allergen.</p>

