        <!-- ─────────────────── 8. FARNESENE ─────────────────── -->
        <h3 id="farnesene" class="wp-subsection-heading">8. trans-&beta;-Farnesene</h3>

        <div class="wp-terpene-profile">
          <strong>Profile:</strong> Sesquiterpene (C<sub>15</sub>H<sub>24</sub>) with a green apple, fruity aroma. &beta;-Farnesene is found in apples&rsquo; coating (hence the smell) and in some cannabis strains in trace amounts. Farnesene (various isomers &alpha;, &beta;) also occurs in chamomile and turmeric. It&rsquo;s one of the lesser-studied cannabis terpenes, but worth mentioning for completeness. Boiling point: approximately 240&thinsp;&deg;C. Colorless oily liquid; hydrophobic. Prone to oxidation. Odor: Green, sweet, apple-like and woody.
        </div>

        <p><strong>Receptor Targets:</strong> Not well characterized. Farnesene likely doesn&rsquo;t bind cannabinoid or major CNS receptors directly. It may act on <strong>TRP channels</strong> &mdash; one study showed farnesene could activate TRPV1 slightly (but much weaker than myrcene). Possibly modulates <strong>voltage-gated ion channels</strong> giving a muscle relaxant effect (speculative).</p>

        <p><strong>Mechanisms of Action:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Anti-spasm/Relaxant:</strong> Farnesene has been reported in herbal medicine contexts to relax smooth muscle &mdash; for example, the volatile oils of chamomile (with farnesene) relax intestinal spasm, contributing to chamomile&rsquo;s GI soothing effect.</li>
          <li><strong>Sedative:</strong> Farnesene might contribute to sedation in chamomile along with other terpenes; however, its sedative capacity is probably mild.</li>
          <li><strong>Anti-inflammatory:</strong> There is some evidence farnesene has anti-inflammatory activity &mdash; an experiment with isolated farnesene showed it inhibited LPS-induced NO production in macrophages (so it may reduce iNOS similar to humulene, but data is limited).</li>
          <li><strong>Anti-oxidant:</strong> Farnesene is an unsaturated hydrocarbon; it can act as a free radical scavenger to a degree and may induce the body&rsquo;s own antioxidant enzymes.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Therapeutic Effects:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Pain/Spasm:</strong> If farnesene relaxes muscles, it could help with mild muscle pain or menstrual cramps.</li>
          <li><strong>Anxiety/Stress:</strong> The smell of green apples is oddly known to reduce anxiety in some studies (one hospital trial found that green apple aroma reduced anxiety in pre-op patients). It&rsquo;s possible farnesene has an odor-driven calming effect.</li>
          <li><strong>Anti-inflammatory:</strong> Could aid in conditions like minor skin irritation; supportive but <strong>not a heavy-hitter</strong>.</li>
          <li><strong>Sedation/Sleep:</strong> Farnesene alone likely doesn&rsquo;t cause drowsiness in reasonable amounts, but in synergy with other terpenes it could assist in promoting calm that leads to sleep.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Pharmacokinetics:</strong> If inhaled or ingested, farnesene would behave like other sesquiterpenes: absorb into blood, distribute to tissues, metabolize via CYPs to more polar compounds. Half-life unknown; likely short (couple hours). It is lipophilic, so inhaled farnesene will deposit in fat and muscle. Relatively non-volatile compared to monoterpenes. Orally, as part of an essential oil, it should absorb fine, with first-pass metabolism.</p>

        <p><strong>Synergistic Pairings:</strong> Farnesene often co-exists with <strong>bisabolol</strong> in chamomile and with <strong>limonene</strong> in citrus, so synergy wise: Farnesene + bisabolol in chamomile oil gives both anti-inflammatory and calming GI effects. Farnesene + limonene (like in some fruit-scented strains) could be mood-uplifting and stress relieving. Farnesene might also support <strong>sedative combos</strong> by adding a gentle relaxant layer, though by itself it&rsquo;s subtle. It&rsquo;s a background terpene that rounds out the profile rather than drives it.</p>

        <p><strong>Drug Interactions:</strong> Nothing known. Given it&rsquo;s in food (apples) and widely consumed, it&rsquo;s likely benign in this regard at normal exposures. It doesn&rsquo;t sedate strongly, doesn&rsquo;t inhibit major enzymes known.</p>

        <p><strong>Toxicity &amp; Safety:</strong> Farnesene hasn&rsquo;t shown any notable toxicity. Apple-derived farnesene is used as a food flavor (artificial apple flavor) and considered safe in that context. Overexposure could theoretically cause headache or irritation (any strong fragrance can), but it&rsquo;s one of the more pleasant and low-irritation terpenes. No evidence of mutagenicity or carcinogenicity at normal doses.</p>

