        <!-- ─────────────────── 9. BISABOLOL ─────────────────── -->
        <h3 id="bisabolol" class="wp-subsection-heading">9. Bisabolol (&alpha;-Bisabolol)</h3>

        <div class="wp-terpene-profile">
          <strong>Profile:</strong> Sesquiterpene alcohol (C<sub>15</sub>H<sub>26</sub>O) with a mild sweet floral aroma (primary scent of chamomile). Also present in cannabis in small amounts. Known for skin-soothing properties. <em>(Due to length, a brief summary.)</em>
        </div>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Targets:</strong> Anti-irritant/anti-inflammatory via COX-2 and IL-6 inhibition. Binds to <strong>TRPV3</strong> (chamomile&rsquo;s warmth sensation) and <strong>TRPA1</strong> (reduces pain signalling when desensitized). Some affinity for <strong>&mu;-opioid receptors</strong> reported in silico (unconfirmed in vivo). Antioxidant. Mild antimicrobial.</li>
          <li><strong>Effects:</strong> <em>Anti-inflammatory and skin-healing</em> &mdash; reduces dermatitis, used in cosmetics for soothing. Some analgesic effect (especially for skin/mucous membrane pain). <em>Anxiolytic (mild)</em> &mdash; chamomile&rsquo;s calmative effects partly from bisabolol (along with apigenin). <em>Ulcer-protective</em> &mdash; bisabolol helps heal gastric ulcers (perhaps by increasing mucus and reducing inflammation).</li>
          <li><strong>PK:</strong> Well absorbed orally and topically. Metabolized to bisabolol oxide. Very safe (used in foods/cosmetics extensively).</li>
          <li><strong>Synergy:</strong> Works with chamomile&rsquo;s other actives for anti-anxiety and GI relief. In cannabis, likely supports anti-inflammatory and anti-ulcer effects of CBD/THC.</li>
          <li><strong>Safety:</strong> Non-toxic. Gentle on skin, even suitable for baby products.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><em>(Bisabolol is included for completeness as a notable terpene though evidence in cannabis context is limited.)</em></p>

