        <!-- ─────────────────── 10. EUCALYPTOL ─────────────────── -->
        <h3 id="eucalyptol" class="wp-subsection-heading">10. Eucalyptol (1,8-Cineole)</h3>

        <div class="wp-terpene-profile">
          <strong>Profile:</strong> Monoterpene ether (C<sub>10</sub>H<sub>18</sub>O) with a brisk, camphoraceous minty aroma (the scent of eucalyptus). Minor in most cannabis strains, but some (like certain sativa landraces) have noticeable cineole. Often used medically as an expectorant and anti-inflammatory. <em>(Brief summary.)</em>
        </div>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Receptor Targets:</strong> <strong>TRPM8 agonist</strong> (cooling receptor &mdash; gives that cooling sensation similar to menthol). <strong>AChE inhibitor</strong> (like pinene &mdash; improves cholinergic neurotransmission, enhancing cognition). Also a <strong>weak NMDA receptor antagonist</strong> (contributing to central analgesia). Possibly <strong>&beta;<sub>2</sub>-adrenergic agonist</strong> (explains bronchodilation).</li>
          <li><strong>Mechanisms:</strong> <strong>Bronchodilation</strong> &mdash; relaxes airway smooth muscle, improving asthma symptoms. <strong>Anti-inflammatory</strong> &mdash; especially in airways; cineole reduces cytokine production (IL-1&beta;, TNF) in bronchial cells and can improve sinusitis. <strong>Analgesic</strong> &mdash; mild; partly via anti-inflammatory effect and possibly central action (NMDA antagonism reduces excitatory pain transmission). <strong>Cognitive enhancement</strong> &mdash; in aromatherapy studies, cineole correlated with improved memory recall. <strong>Antimicrobial</strong> &mdash; potent against bacteria. <strong>Stimulant</strong> &mdash; at low doses it can increase alertness.</li>
          <li><strong>Therapeutic:</strong> <strong>Respiratory</strong> &mdash; Cineole is an approved medicine for bronchitis and sinusitis in Europe (clears mucus, reduces inflammation). <strong>Cognition</strong> &mdash; might offset THC brain fog as discussed with pinene; indeed rosemary (cineole) improved prospective memory in human tests. <strong>Pain</strong> &mdash; cineole ointments help some muscle pain (via counterirritation and reducing inflammation). <strong>Infections</strong> &mdash; might help keep lungs sterile in medical cannabis inhalation.</li>
          <li><strong>PK:</strong> <strong>Oral</strong> &mdash; well absorbed, peak around 1&ndash;2h, largely excreted in urine as cineole-1,2-diol glucuronide. <strong>Inhaled</strong> &mdash; rapidly absorbed, peaks within minutes, significant portion exhaled unchanged (characteristic eucalyptus smell on breath). T<sub>&frac12;</sub> likely ~1&ndash;3h. Crosses BBB readily.</li>
          <li><strong>Synergy:</strong> <strong>With pinene</strong> &mdash; both are bronchodilators and cognitive aids, likely additive for clear-headed effect. <strong>With THC</strong> &mdash; may reduce cough from smoking and sharpen the high. <strong>With CBD</strong> &mdash; could improve focus and relieve nasal congestion. <strong>As entourage</strong> &mdash; included in some &ldquo;focus&rdquo; terpene blends with pinene and limonene.</li>
          <li><strong>Safety:</strong> <strong>Inhalation</strong> &mdash; at medicinal doses safe, high concentrations can cause airway irritation or even CNS signs (very high cineole &mdash; remember eucalyptus oil poisoning in kids). But amounts in cannabis are tiny. <strong>Pregnancy</strong> &mdash; generally considered okay in small inhaled amounts (like in vapor rubs), but ingestion of large cineole (eucalyptus oil) not recommended. <strong>Overall</strong> &mdash; cineole is quite safe; it&rsquo;s in lozenges and chest rubs OTC. Therapeutic dose in bronchitis is ~200 mg cineole daily, which is far above what one would inhale from cannabis.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><em>Note: Many other terpenes (camphene, terpinene, ocimene, guaiol, etc.) exist in cannabis in trace levels and have various effects (antioxidant, antifungal, decongestant). Due to space, we focused on key ones above.</em></p>

